  "doc_id": "45875",
  "text": "The puncture of the desired calix can be done in dilated systems. If only the renal pelvic can be identified, initial puncture can be done at renal pelvic following with antegrade pyelography for secondary definitive caliceal puncture. Ultrasound guidance is helpful in determining the depth and the angle of approach. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Real time ultrasound is widely used for percutaneous access of a dilated collecting system and is beneficial in infants, pregnant women and patients following renal transplantation. [CITATION_3] . The disadvantage of percutaneous nephrostomy access by ultrasound guidance, this guidance system may be compromised by rib artifacts. (Fig. 6, 7 ) ",
